column2: How familiar are you with your company's immigration policies?

column7: Do you have a written immigration policy today?
column8: Does your company hire candidates on H-1B visas?
column9: Do you require that the H-1B candidate has a minimum amount of time remaining in their overall 6-year maximum for them to be eligible for hire?
column10: How many months must be remaining in their H-1B status (time before max out)? Please leave blank if unsure; use the arrow button below to move forward.
column12: Are H-1B employees eligible for Green Card sponsorship?
column13: How many months after the employee's start date are H-1B employees eligible for initiation of a Green Card process?Please leave blank if unsure; use the arrow button below to move forward.
column14: Months after start date for GC eligibility from H-1B (modified)
column15: Does your company sponsor L-1 visas?
column16: Are L-1 employees eligible for H-1B lottery sponsorship?

column18: Months before eligible for H-1B from L-1 (modified)
column19: Are L-1 employees eligible for Green Card sponsorship?
column20: How many months after the L-1 employee's start date are they eligible for initiation of a Green Card process?Please leave blank if unsure; use the arrow button below to move forward.
column21: Months after start date for GC eligibility from L-1 (modified)
column22: Does your company sponsor F-1 OPT visas?
column23: Do you require that the F-1 OPT candidate has a minimum time period of OPT or STEM OPT remaining for them to be eligible for hire?
column24: How many months must be remaining in their F-1 status (time before max out)?Please leave blank if unsure; use the arrow button below to move forward.
column26: Does your company sponsor single intent visas (e.g. TN, E-2, E-3, O-1) that can be renewed indefinitely?
column27: Are single intent visa employees eligible for H-1B lottery sponsorship?

column32: Months after start-date for GC eligibility from single intent (modified)
column33: How many months before an employee's status expiration do you initiate an extension?Please leave blank if unsure; use the arrow button below to move forward.
column34: Months left before expiry to initiate extension (modified)
column35: When are employees eligible to start with your company after an H-1B transfer has been filed?
column36: Does your company support the maintenance of the employee's underlying nonimmigrant visa once an I-485 is pending?
column37: Do you limit which occupations/jobs you are willing to sponsor for a non-immigrant visa?
column38: To show that you are paying attention, please select "none of the above" option as your answer.
column39: For PERM-based Green Cards, the employer is required to cover the cost of the PERM but either the employer or employee can cover the cost of the I-140 and I-485 processes. What portion of I-140 costs do you cover?
column40: What portion of I-485 costs do you cover?
column41: Do you cover Green Card processing costs for the employee's dependent family members?
column42: If an application is filed with USCIS' Premium Processing option, who covers the cost?
column43: What portion of consular processing costs do you cover when an employee goes abroad to obtain a visa stamp?
column44: Will you cover travel expenses related to consular processing of visa applications?
column46: Do you cover non-immigrant visa costs for the employee's dependent family members?
column47: Do you have a liquidated damages clause that allows you to recoup immigration fees when an employee leaves your company within a specific time period?
column48: What is the tenure threshold below which the liquidated damages clause applies in months?Please leave blank if unsure; use the arrow button below to move forward.
column50: What percent of damages are you seeking to recover?Please leave blank if unsure; use the arrow button below to move forward.
column52: Who is responsible for immigration costs at your company?
column53: Do you share a complete copy of an employee's immigration filings with the employee to bring to consular appointments?
